Language: en

00:00:00.260 --> 00:00:02.000
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Hello everyone.

00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:04.310
Welcome to another edition of Authors at Google.

00:00:04.310 --> 00:00:09.360
We're very excited to have Renee Montagne
with us today, co-host of "Morning Edition."

00:00:09.360 --> 00:00:14.640
I don't know how many of you are actually
up at that time of day.

00:00:14.640 --> 00:00:15.640
[laughter]

00:00:15.640 --> 00:00:16.640
So, maybe?

00:00:16.640 --> 00:00:17.640
I don't know.

00:00:17.640 --> 00:00:18.640
I usually am.

00:00:18.640 --> 00:00:19.920
So, as I'm driving to work, I usually listen
to the show.

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:21.420
So I'm very excited.

00:00:21.420 --> 00:00:25.520
The book is "This is NPR, The First Forty
Years."

00:00:25.520 --> 00:00:31.800
It's great for me to be able to put some faces
to the voices that I hear on NPR every day.

00:00:31.800 --> 00:00:37.390
And it's great to hear some of the stories--all
the exciting people they meet, all the great

00:00:37.390 --> 00:00:39.389
events they cover.

00:00:39.389 --> 00:00:42.059
So, no further introduction.

00:00:42.059 --> 00:00:43.389
Renee Montagne.

00:00:43.389 --> 00:00:44.389
[applause]

00:00:44.389 --> 00:00:46.479
&gt;&gt;Renee Montagne: Thank you very much.

00:00:46.479 --> 00:00:47.479
Thank you, Mike, for the introduction.

00:00:47.479 --> 00:00:53.230
I hope you, I'm imagining those in this room
probably do listen to "Morning Edition," or

00:00:53.230 --> 00:00:56.999
you certainly listen to NPR shows, which is
what this book is about.

00:00:56.999 --> 00:01:01.729
And in order, in fact, to talk about the book
is to talk about NPR.

00:01:01.729 --> 00:01:06.060
But I just have to say one thing, which I
will say to anybody, I love Google.

00:01:06.060 --> 00:01:07.060
[laughter]

00:01:07.060 --> 00:01:11.990
And I actually, it's almost hard to imagine
living without it and doing what we do without

00:01:11.990 --> 00:01:12.990
it.

00:01:12.990 --> 00:01:16.050
And one of the interesting things about doing
this book, which, of course, now it's the

00:01:16.050 --> 00:01:20.050
forty-first, this now it's the 41 years of
NPR.

00:01:20.050 --> 00:01:26.030
When we were doing this book, like not last
year, but the year before, and each of--.

00:01:26.030 --> 00:01:31.680
There are four decade chapters and they were
given to four different authors to do the

00:01:31.680 --> 00:01:33.310
chapters.

00:01:33.310 --> 00:01:40.260
It was such an amazing walk down like, remembering
what life was like without Google basically,

00:01:40.260 --> 00:01:47.270
and everything else that's come onto the scene
in the last, sometimes five years.

00:01:47.270 --> 00:01:50.060
The last ten, the last decade anyway.

00:01:50.060 --> 00:01:56.330
And things like we now have--I'm jumping ahead
here, but I just wanna say--we now have, we

00:01:56.330 --> 00:02:01.830
now have people we interview, we ask them
to record themselves on their iPhones.

00:02:01.830 --> 00:02:07.340
And it's like something out of like, the future,
to be able to say there's a microphone and

00:02:07.340 --> 00:02:12.099
the quality, unless you really screw up, will
be really good.

00:02:12.099 --> 00:02:14.080
And do you mind just recording yourself?

00:02:14.080 --> 00:02:19.049
I mean, that, I couldn't have made that one
up even years ago.

00:02:19.049 --> 00:02:23.810
So, anyway, I'm delighted to talk about the
book because I think for those of you, and

00:02:23.810 --> 00:02:27.469
there is, I was thinking maybe it would be
a group where nobody would've been born by

00:02:27.469 --> 00:02:28.469
the beginning of NPR.

00:02:28.469 --> 00:02:32.239
But the fact, some of you look like you were
born back then.

00:02:32.239 --> 00:02:37.719
So, some of you might recognize some of what
I'm going to talk about.

00:02:37.719 --> 00:02:43.219
As I say, there were four, lots of contributors
and introductions--Susan Stamberg, Cokie Roberts.

00:02:43.219 --> 00:02:49.900
Susan talks about--I wasn't there--but in
1971, in May 3rd, when the show went on the

00:02:49.900 --> 00:02:53.390
air, in the weeks leading up to that, they
had meetings.

00:02:53.390 --> 00:02:55.779
This is how NPR began.

00:02:55.779 --> 00:02:56.779
They had meetings.

00:02:56.779 --> 00:03:01.510
They all sat on the floor, figured out what
the mission was and many things that they

00:03:01.510 --> 00:03:08.230
were, as they were trying to literally bring
into being this entity, National Public Radio.

00:03:08.230 --> 00:03:10.400
And they sat on the floor.

00:03:10.400 --> 00:03:14.629
And Susan had told me that story once or twice
and I never realized that until she wrote

00:03:14.629 --> 00:03:18.249
her introduction, that the reason that they
sat on the floor wasn't because they all were

00:03:18.249 --> 00:03:21.279
a bunch of hippies, but because there were
no chairs.

00:03:21.279 --> 00:03:22.279
[laughter]

00:03:22.279 --> 00:03:28.829
NPR had, was that, they hadn't literally bought
the chairs yet when "All Things Considered"

00:03:28.829 --> 00:03:30.959
first went on the air.

00:03:30.959 --> 00:03:35.219
And so, there were these contributions by
all kinds of people.

00:03:35.219 --> 00:03:39.510
And as I say, the four chapters, and for those
of you who have books, I'll tell you literally--if

00:03:39.510 --> 00:03:43.999
you wanna know--what's say, my writing or
Ari Shapiro's writing.

00:03:43.999 --> 00:03:44.999
It's the white pages.

00:03:44.999 --> 00:03:53.669
[laughs] And then all the rest are maybe really
the best part, are these inserts, the side

00:03:53.669 --> 00:03:59.639
bars, which are personal stories from a whole
range of people--how they got to NPR, what

00:03:59.639 --> 00:04:04.819
they did.

00:04:04.819 --> 00:04:08.379
There's also transcripts, which are nice.

00:04:08.379 --> 00:04:12.029
And they picked ones that did work on the
page, but it's interesting to see some of

00:04:12.029 --> 00:04:18.570
this stuff written down when the whole essence
of what we do is for the ear and is in storytelling

00:04:18.570 --> 00:04:19.710
mode.

00:04:19.710 --> 00:04:26.370
So, I'm just gonna begin with my own chapter,
which is the 90s, which is an era of NPR that

00:04:26.370 --> 00:04:28.920
was a great turning point for NPR.

00:04:28.920 --> 00:04:35.570
I mean, I think it's safe to say that up until
the end of the 80s, NPR was a well-kept secret.

00:04:35.570 --> 00:04:41.880
I mean, it was, what's that expression for
when like, a few people know about something

00:04:41.880 --> 00:04:46.510
and they're really dedicated, but the world
at large isn't that familiar?

00:04:46.510 --> 00:04:50.870
I traveled through Texas to do a story on
a tornado where you could travel for seven,

00:04:50.870 --> 00:04:55.100
eight hours and never pick up an NPR station.

00:04:55.100 --> 00:05:00.920
And also through Nebraska in 1988, the whole
western side of Nebraska, you could not pick

00:05:00.920 --> 00:05:02.290
up an NPR station.

00:05:02.290 --> 00:05:06.290
And that all changed in about two or three
years.

00:05:06.290 --> 00:05:11.420
There's no place you can go now and theoretically,
if you're not right in the mountains, pick

00:05:11.420 --> 00:05:13.340
up an NPR station.

00:05:13.340 --> 00:05:18.390
And one of the things that changed it, actually,
was our foreign coverage.

00:05:18.390 --> 00:05:23.030
We were very, to the degree that NPR was known,
people knew Cokie Roberts.

00:05:23.030 --> 00:05:27.020
I mean, she made her name on NPR before she
went over to ABC.

00:05:27.020 --> 00:05:28.790
They knew Linda Wertheimer.

00:05:28.790 --> 00:05:32.680
They knew the people who covered Washington.

00:05:32.680 --> 00:05:36.750
And to the degree that it was known and very
respected by the time, I was freelancing at

00:05:36.750 --> 00:05:40.210
that time, it was because of that sort of
coverage.

00:05:40.210 --> 00:05:48.630
That and a certain amount of reaching out
to the small towns of the country in innovative

00:05:48.630 --> 00:05:57.190
ways, because whereas we now have stations
like KPCC that have full service news departments,

00:05:57.190 --> 00:05:59.910
in those days, pretty much we didn't even
have that.

00:05:59.910 --> 00:06:07.290
I mean, we had a Washington contingent and
we had, in the 80s, I can't give you an exact

00:06:07.290 --> 00:06:11.240
count, but there were maybe ten staff reporters
in the country, maybe.

00:06:11.240 --> 00:06:16.580
I mean, I can remember there was America Rodriguez
here in Los Angeles.

00:06:16.580 --> 00:06:17.580
That was her name.

00:06:17.580 --> 00:06:19.760
She went on to other things, but America Rodriguez.

00:06:19.760 --> 00:06:23.970
There was Scott Simon in Chicago.

00:06:23.970 --> 00:06:26.280
There was, I mean, you could name them practically.

00:06:26.280 --> 00:06:27.360
In fact, I might be wrong.

00:06:27.360 --> 00:06:30.590
There might have only been five national correspondents.

00:06:30.590 --> 00:06:36.350
And there was no foreign, there was one foreign
correspondent and that was, it was Robert

00:06:36.350 --> 00:06:42.380
Siegel in a chunk of the 80s because we had
a location and still do, although it's not

00:06:42.380 --> 00:06:44.010
Bush House anymore.

00:06:44.010 --> 00:06:51.610
We had studios in Bush House as of, I think,
1979 or '80.

00:06:51.610 --> 00:06:54.390
Sylvia Poggioli, for instance, I used to chatter
with her.

00:06:54.390 --> 00:06:58.710
You had the fun of talking with people that
I know very well, but I really see 'cause

00:06:58.710 --> 00:07:01.500
NPR, all our friends are people in other places.

00:07:01.500 --> 00:07:07.040
You become friends with somebody that you
have never lived in the same town or city.

00:07:07.040 --> 00:07:11.540
And Sylvia's one of the long time friends
who I don't ever hardly get to sit and have

00:07:11.540 --> 00:07:14.620
an in-depth conversation with, but I did for
the book, which was fun.

00:07:14.620 --> 00:07:18.200
And I said, "Sylvia, when did you actually
go on staff?"

00:07:18.200 --> 00:07:20.730
And Sylvie said, "Let's put it this way.

00:07:20.730 --> 00:07:23.620
They'd already named the restaurant after
me."

00:07:23.620 --> 00:07:26.280
And what she meant was that she was so famous.

00:07:26.280 --> 00:07:28.460
I mean, Sylvia Poggioli.

00:07:28.460 --> 00:07:34.740
She was so part of the fabric of NPR, of the
sound of NPR, that you couldn't believe that

00:07:34.740 --> 00:07:37.110
she was still on a contract.

00:07:37.110 --> 00:07:42.230
I mean, not on a contract, 'till 1993.

00:07:42.230 --> 00:07:44.690
And she'd been ten years working with NPR.

00:07:44.690 --> 00:07:48.560
And the restaurant was this restaurant in
Salem, Oregon called Poggioli's.

00:07:48.560 --> 00:07:50.080
There were actually two at one point.

00:07:50.080 --> 00:07:55.460
And she was like already surfing, what's the
New York Times, more recently, was talking

00:07:55.460 --> 00:07:59.050
about something that happened in the Vatican
and said, "Holy Poggioli.

00:07:59.050 --> 00:08:00.050
It's blah-dy, blah-dy, blah."

00:08:00.050 --> 00:08:02.470
It was a jokey thing about the Vatican.

00:08:02.470 --> 00:08:10.500
So, it's almost impossible to imagine how
well NPR covered the country when we didn't

00:08:10.500 --> 00:08:12.670
have reporters out in the country.

00:08:12.670 --> 00:08:15.071
And we had some freelance, a lot of freelance
people.

00:08:15.071 --> 00:08:16.071
I was freelance.

00:08:16.071 --> 00:08:17.389
I mean, there was no hope of getting--.

00:08:17.389 --> 00:08:21.440
I was in New York, no hope of getting a job
in the '80s because they were, like I said,

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:23.889
there was Margot Adler, the same people who--.

00:08:23.889 --> 00:08:25.970
We're like, "They're gonna have to die."

00:08:25.970 --> 00:08:26.970
Thank God.

00:08:26.970 --> 00:08:28.060
I mean, they didn't.

00:08:28.060 --> 00:08:29.060
[laughter]

00:08:29.060 --> 00:08:33.510
They didn't and there's three people still
there who are were there back in the '80s.

00:08:33.510 --> 00:08:37.169
But when they asked me to do the '90s, it
was a great thing because I had just come

00:08:37.169 --> 00:08:40.100
on staff officially in '88.

00:08:40.100 --> 00:08:44.500
And I, as the host, the co-host with Robert
Siegel of "All Things Considered," when Susan

00:08:44.500 --> 00:08:47.650
Stamberg and Noah Adams left.

00:08:47.650 --> 00:08:52.700
And I did that for a couple of years and then,
starting in '90, I started going to South

00:08:52.700 --> 00:08:53.700
Africa.

00:08:53.700 --> 00:09:00.180
And so, I had a taste of what are the new
level that NPR was gonna reach when foreign

00:09:00.180 --> 00:09:06.250
coverage became one of our best projects.

00:09:06.250 --> 00:09:13.180
And it also, the foreign coverage that NPR
provides for some parts of the country is

00:09:13.180 --> 00:09:17.210
all the foreign coverage that anybody's gonna
get there.

00:09:17.210 --> 00:09:21.470
I went to South Africa to cover the release
of Nelson Mandela.

00:09:21.470 --> 00:09:22.870
One of the biggest stories of the decade.

00:09:22.870 --> 00:09:28.590
Actually, one of the biggest stories, the
Mandela story, of the century.

00:09:28.590 --> 00:09:32.279
And I got there the day, literally the day
he was released.

00:09:32.279 --> 00:09:37.170
And I remember it was raining and I started
the chapter with that it was raining in Soweto,

00:09:37.170 --> 00:09:42.060
which in Africa, I was soon to learn, a positive.

00:09:42.060 --> 00:09:43.630
Rain is considered a gift.

00:09:43.630 --> 00:09:49.340
And it was considered very, very propitious--a
very, very good sign.

00:09:49.340 --> 00:09:52.840
And I got there the day that he was released.

00:09:52.840 --> 00:09:57.720
And the idea was NPR was turning more and
more to trying to be there for these big events.

00:09:57.720 --> 00:09:59.930
We had been there for the fall of the Berlin
Wall.

00:09:59.930 --> 00:10:03.640
They sent Robert Siegel just the year before.

00:10:03.640 --> 00:10:09.910
We had been there, we had people in Poland
when solidarity prevailed and they elected

00:10:09.910 --> 00:10:13.210
Walesa as President.

00:10:13.210 --> 00:10:18.670
We, all this stuff was stunningly over about
a two-year period, the world literally was

00:10:18.670 --> 00:10:19.670
changing.

00:10:19.670 --> 00:10:24.230
And at that moment in time, what was happening
was the Cold War was ending and walls were

00:10:24.230 --> 00:10:25.230
coming down.

00:10:25.230 --> 00:10:32.100
So, it was really a moment that's actually
almost impossible to imagine now of such hope.

00:10:32.100 --> 00:10:39.231
A little like the Arab Spring, only with much
more, how can I say, much more of a potential

00:10:39.231 --> 00:10:42.580
for positive outcomes, like in Poland, in
Russia.

00:10:42.580 --> 00:10:46.360
And it was Russia before the oligarchs, Russia
before Putin.

00:10:46.360 --> 00:10:50.640
This was like a new Russia emerging it seemed.

00:10:50.640 --> 00:11:00.630
And to give you a feel for how it worked then,
I showed up, got myself in a car, got on the

00:11:00.630 --> 00:11:06.810
left side of the road, started driving where
the big networks were in a four-star hotel

00:11:06.810 --> 00:11:07.810
downtown.

00:11:07.810 --> 00:11:12.470
A downtown, by the way, that was soon to disappear
and become very African.

00:11:12.470 --> 00:11:15.040
But at that exact moment in time, it was very
white.

00:11:15.040 --> 00:11:17.430
And it was called the Golden Mile.

00:11:17.430 --> 00:11:21.460
So, all the fancy restaurants, because apartheid,
right?

00:11:21.460 --> 00:11:26.520
Obviously, the wealth was downtown, like it
would be in a normal city.

00:11:26.520 --> 00:11:32.110
Well, NPR had us out in the suburbs and we
were in this little hotel that was really

00:11:32.110 --> 00:11:33.430
a salesmen hotel.

00:11:33.430 --> 00:11:36.430
And I don't know if you know Afrikaners, but
they're like the--I don't know what you would

00:11:36.430 --> 00:11:37.430
say.

00:11:37.430 --> 00:11:40.980
Well, they're the white people of South Africa,
but Afrikaners in particular, they would be

00:11:40.980 --> 00:11:42.590
out in the countryside and in small towns.

00:11:42.590 --> 00:11:46.760
So, it was like Afrikaner’s salesmen who
were living at, were staying there.

00:11:46.760 --> 00:11:51.770
And here we flow in and there were five of
us and we set up shop.

00:11:51.770 --> 00:11:56.930
And the only way we could get out was through
the hotel phone system, which meant that if

00:11:56.930 --> 00:12:00.630
somebody called you, like, say you were trying
to set up an interview.

00:12:00.630 --> 00:12:05.101
You would call out and, of course, most people
in South Africa did not have landlines, not

00:12:05.101 --> 00:12:06.101
just the black people.

00:12:06.101 --> 00:12:09.450
A lot of white people didn't either 'cause
they just didn't have a good phone system.

00:12:09.450 --> 00:12:11.190
There was no such thing as cell phones.

00:12:11.190 --> 00:12:14.310
The political people were pretty sophisticated.

00:12:14.310 --> 00:12:17.210
They had--what do you call it?

00:12:17.210 --> 00:12:18.250
Pagers.

00:12:18.250 --> 00:12:23.170
And all you could do is put your number down
and cross your fingers that they would page

00:12:23.170 --> 00:12:25.970
you back or call you back.

00:12:25.970 --> 00:12:31.760
But in our case, it went through a hotel system
where, if you were out you wouldn't get the

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:32.760
call.

00:12:32.760 --> 00:12:34.870
If you were upstairs and they knocked on your
door and you were in the bathroom you wouldn't

00:12:34.870 --> 00:12:35.870
get the call.

00:12:35.870 --> 00:12:39.290
I mean, it was like, really hard to set up
an interview.

00:12:39.290 --> 00:12:44.070
So basically, you had to go to the place,
set the interview up, and hope that they were

00:12:44.070 --> 00:12:47.660
there when you came back for the appointed
time, or if they were there, hope they were

00:12:47.660 --> 00:12:49.620
willing to talk to you.

00:12:49.620 --> 00:12:57.970
It didn't hurt me too much because I was there
to cover people, not the Mandela people, not

00:12:57.970 --> 00:12:59.620
the ANC--the African National Congress.

00:12:59.620 --> 00:13:02.570
But when we wanted to file, I had to file.

00:13:02.570 --> 00:13:03.820
And I'm gonna actually have to look this up.

00:13:03.820 --> 00:13:05.220
It's called, something called the--.

00:13:05.220 --> 00:13:12.420
What you filed on was something called a Comrex
and Vince Mews, our engineer, set it all up.

00:13:12.420 --> 00:13:19.730
And it was one of these things that you would
do your, you would talk into it and then it

00:13:19.730 --> 00:13:26.050
would slow--not a time thing--but they stretched
it out and then they closed it back up at

00:13:26.050 --> 00:13:28.930
the other end, which meant that it didn't
always sound right.

00:13:28.930 --> 00:13:33.820
I mean, it sometimes sounded slightly off
in this funny way, but that was the best you

00:13:33.820 --> 00:13:35.060
could do.

00:13:35.060 --> 00:13:37.770
And as for the rest, you were on your own.

00:13:37.770 --> 00:13:40.440
Like, you got in your car and went out and
found people.

00:13:40.440 --> 00:13:41.440
And I used to this.

00:13:41.440 --> 00:13:46.880
I had a technique and I was in and out of
the country for the next four years through

00:13:46.880 --> 00:13:53.140
Mandela's inauguration and lived there at
times for as much as a year.

00:13:53.140 --> 00:13:58.430
And at all times, I just would go into the
townships, even, there are these township

00:13:58.430 --> 00:14:01.410
wars that grew up and there was two years
and it was pretty serious business.

00:14:01.410 --> 00:14:04.500
It doesn't sound like anything now, but they
were fighting each other and killing each

00:14:04.500 --> 00:14:06.170
other in the townships.

00:14:06.170 --> 00:14:07.340
And it was a strange war.

00:14:07.340 --> 00:14:11.810
It was between the Zulu and Khartoum Freedom
Party, which was ethnic and the ANC, which

00:14:11.810 --> 00:14:13.020
wasn't ethnic.

00:14:13.020 --> 00:14:15.620
But this was a power struggle.

00:14:15.620 --> 00:14:19.720
And so, these young guys, comrades, they called
themselves on the ANC side.

00:14:19.720 --> 00:14:21.670
And you'll probably remember them from the
'80s.

00:14:21.670 --> 00:14:23.690
Kids would be out there protesting.

00:14:23.690 --> 00:14:25.730
And they were young kids.

00:14:25.730 --> 00:14:28.550
It was almost like a children's revolution
in that sense.

00:14:28.550 --> 00:14:30.390
They were young teenagers and whatnot.

00:14:30.390 --> 00:14:34.260
They would, I would just get, I would find
somebody and get them in my car.

00:14:34.260 --> 00:14:36.160
And Soweto had two million people.

00:14:36.160 --> 00:14:37.430
It was the township of Soweto.

00:14:37.430 --> 00:14:38.540
It had two million people.

00:14:38.540 --> 00:14:41.350
It did not have a single street sign.

00:14:41.350 --> 00:14:42.760
It did not have--.

00:14:42.760 --> 00:14:47.360
If you wanted to go somewhere, there were
a couple of things like Baragwanath Hospital.

00:14:47.360 --> 00:14:51.190
And there are a couple of things, but it was
this sprawling township.

00:14:51.190 --> 00:14:56.600
And you would go in and there was like nothing
else you could do but have some local person

00:14:56.600 --> 00:14:59.240
take you where you wanted to go and everyone
needed a ride.

00:14:59.240 --> 00:15:02.200
I mean, I'd be the only car driving along.

00:15:02.200 --> 00:15:06.610
And I'd look out at somebody likely and often
it would be these young guys, kids, that wanted

00:15:06.610 --> 00:15:07.980
to get in your car.

00:15:07.980 --> 00:15:08.980
And so they came.

00:15:08.980 --> 00:15:12.650
But when it came time to filing, this is how
we filed.

00:15:12.650 --> 00:15:16.010
There were two ways to file, and this one
on the whole time I was there, through '94,

00:15:16.010 --> 00:15:17.270
right through the inauguration.

00:15:17.270 --> 00:15:19.440
When it came time to filing, you had two choices.

00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:25.240
If you had a really, really nice feature story
and you wanted to put it on a nice tape, I

00:15:25.240 --> 00:15:32.660
would, I had rigged up in my bedroom a quilt
over a chair for sound purposes.

00:15:32.660 --> 00:15:33.750
And I would sit under it.

00:15:33.750 --> 00:15:36.440
And I swear to God, I never got it right,
ever in all that time.

00:15:36.440 --> 00:15:38.890
And it would fall on my head all the time.

00:15:38.890 --> 00:15:45.220
But you would put this quilt up and get down
and do my tracks, put them on a cassette,

00:15:45.220 --> 00:15:46.220
send the cassette--.

00:15:46.220 --> 00:15:47.220
[laughter]

00:15:47.220 --> 00:15:52.029
Sometimes, I actually had a machine that I
could edit it on, so I'm not saying I'd always

00:15:52.029 --> 00:15:53.029
send it this way.

00:15:53.029 --> 00:15:58.200
I would often edit it to my satisfaction and
then put it on reel-to-reel.

00:15:58.200 --> 00:15:59.810
But it all started with a cassette.

00:15:59.810 --> 00:16:01.050
That was how I recorded it.

00:16:01.050 --> 00:16:03.149
And then the cassettes of my tapes--.

00:16:03.149 --> 00:16:04.480
So, I'd put it not together.

00:16:04.480 --> 00:16:07.800
I couldn't produce it, but I would put the
reels together.

00:16:07.800 --> 00:16:12.480
And then, we had an arrangement with the BBC
where there would be a pick-up every day at

00:16:12.480 --> 00:16:15.600
five o'clock in the afternoon, so you had
to be there.

00:16:15.600 --> 00:16:19.550
I would knock on your door, take your tape,
take it down to the airport.

00:16:19.550 --> 00:16:22.779
They would put it on a plane along with the
BBC stuff.

00:16:22.779 --> 00:16:26.720
The BBC would collect it and get it through
customs in London.

00:16:26.720 --> 00:16:28.650
They would get it over to the Bush House.

00:16:28.650 --> 00:16:32.380
And then, at Bush House, they would send it
by satellite to NPR.

00:16:32.380 --> 00:16:38.600
So, if you wanted to sound good, two days
from finish to delivery--after you've done

00:16:38.600 --> 00:16:39.600
everything.

00:16:39.600 --> 00:16:43.390
If you couldn't afford to do that and you
wanted to send a piece or talk to them, be

00:16:43.390 --> 00:16:45.930
interviewed by NPR--and I didn't do a lot
of what you hear now.

00:16:45.930 --> 00:16:48.120
In fact, I probably did one.

00:16:48.120 --> 00:16:54.950
You hear now talks with people, Lourdes Garcia-Navarro,
right in the middle of, not Tienanmen Square,

00:16:54.950 --> 00:16:57.510
right in the middle of--back in the '90s here.

00:16:57.510 --> 00:16:58.750
Back in the middle of--.

00:16:58.750 --> 00:16:59.750
What?

00:16:59.750 --> 00:17:00.750
Well, I'm thinking of--.

00:17:00.750 --> 00:17:02.320
Well, she was also in Egypt, but--.

00:17:02.320 --> 00:17:04.020
[audience calls out answers]

00:17:04.020 --> 00:17:05.290
Yes, thank you.

00:17:05.290 --> 00:17:06.560
Tahrir Square, right?

00:17:06.560 --> 00:17:09.120
But Lourdes Garcia-Navarro in the middle of
Libya.

00:17:09.120 --> 00:17:10.220
"Hey, Lulu.

00:17:10.220 --> 00:17:12.120
How are you doing?"

00:17:12.120 --> 00:17:15.250
And often, by the way, we do say, "Take care
of yourself," and things you don't hear on

00:17:15.250 --> 00:17:16.830
the air at the end.

00:17:16.830 --> 00:17:21.140
Believe me, I'm highly aware, people are standing
with bullets going by and talking to you.

00:17:21.140 --> 00:17:27.020
Well, then the only way you could talk to
someone, which is why I rarely did any of

00:17:27.020 --> 00:17:34.870
those kinds of conversation--in fact, I never
did--was you, on your tape recorder, you put--.

00:17:34.870 --> 00:17:37.240
I did something.

00:17:37.240 --> 00:17:38.240
You won't even know what this is.

00:17:38.240 --> 00:17:42.270
You took, you unscrewed the telephone and
there are two little prongs, right?

00:17:42.270 --> 00:17:44.210
And then you had alligator clips.

00:17:44.210 --> 00:17:46.390
Have you ever heard of alligator clips?

00:17:46.390 --> 00:17:47.910
They're little electrical things.

00:17:47.910 --> 00:17:49.799
They're, call them alligator clips 'cause
they look like that.

00:17:49.799 --> 00:17:50.850
They're really small.

00:17:50.850 --> 00:17:54.799
You would put it on one, how did it work?

00:17:54.799 --> 00:17:56.000
I know, yes.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:57.170
I can't even remember anymore.

00:17:57.170 --> 00:18:01.890
You would alligator clip it into the telephone
and attach that to the microphone.

00:18:01.890 --> 00:18:06.250
No, to the, geez, recorder.

00:18:06.250 --> 00:18:09.590
But there were, yeah, two clips and it went
into the recorder.

00:18:09.590 --> 00:18:10.590
That's right.

00:18:10.590 --> 00:18:15.799
Then, you would set the recorder on record
and pause.

00:18:15.799 --> 00:18:16.990
Thank you.

00:18:16.990 --> 00:18:17.990
You've got the idea, right?

00:18:17.990 --> 00:18:18.990
Record and pause.

00:18:18.990 --> 00:18:24.179
And then, you would read, which meant you
couldn't talk to somebody because the headset

00:18:24.179 --> 00:18:25.340
is all--.

00:18:25.340 --> 00:18:26.570
You could, technically.

00:18:26.570 --> 00:18:30.490
You could hold it up with these alligator
clips, but you're talking through your microphone,

00:18:30.490 --> 00:18:33.770
so the sound was much, much better going through
the telephone.

00:18:33.770 --> 00:18:37.250
And, or you would record it and just send
everything.

00:18:37.250 --> 00:18:38.920
Just record on cassette and just send everything.

00:18:38.920 --> 00:18:40.080
But it never sounded that good.

00:18:40.080 --> 00:18:41.500
It sounded like telephone tape.

00:18:41.500 --> 00:18:44.570
You would send your tape that way, too, if
you had to.

00:18:44.570 --> 00:18:51.340
And I mean, I'm trying to think of all the
other insane sounding ways in which we communicated.

00:18:51.340 --> 00:18:56.059
Once I was in Congo, in what was then Zaire
and Kinshasa, and it was the very beginning

00:18:56.059 --> 00:19:00.460
of the end of the Mobutu, hung in there for
about eight more years and five million more

00:19:00.460 --> 00:19:01.990
people dead.

00:19:01.990 --> 00:19:07.040
But at that moment in time, he had been a
dictator for like 30 years and there were

00:19:07.040 --> 00:19:08.040
riots.

00:19:08.040 --> 00:19:09.720
And so, you don't--.

00:19:09.720 --> 00:19:13.340
Madhulika Sikka, by the way, who I should
introduce our executive producer of "Morning

00:19:13.340 --> 00:19:18.470
Edition," she just flew in with her daughters
for a vacation and came here on the way from

00:19:18.470 --> 00:19:19.470
the airport.

00:19:19.470 --> 00:19:20.470
But you would like this.

00:19:20.470 --> 00:19:22.350
We had a foreign editor.

00:19:22.350 --> 00:19:23.620
Her name was Cadi Simon.

00:19:23.620 --> 00:19:28.860
At the time, she ran the foreign desk and
was really building the foreign desk.

00:19:28.860 --> 00:19:34.170
She called up once and she said to me, "You
know about the riots?"

00:19:34.170 --> 00:19:36.940
I didn't have wire services 'cause it was
too expensive.

00:19:36.940 --> 00:19:41.640
And also, the phone lines were so bad that
the wire services oftentimes didn't print

00:19:41.640 --> 00:19:42.980
very well in South Africa.

00:19:42.980 --> 00:19:45.660
So Pearce said, "We're not gonna spend hundreds
of dollars.

00:19:45.660 --> 00:19:49.520
You just call us and we'll read it to you."

00:19:49.520 --> 00:19:53.840
And so, I used to call the newscast and they
would read me what was of importance in South

00:19:53.840 --> 00:19:55.750
Africa 'cause I was covering the whole country.

00:19:55.750 --> 00:20:01.960
So, clearly, I covered it with features for
the most part and not a daily, daily thing.

00:20:01.960 --> 00:20:03.000
But she called me.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:04.100
She said there's riots.

00:20:04.100 --> 00:20:09.679
And she said, "and they're talking about--"
and there's the fewest Europeans in Zaire

00:20:09.679 --> 00:20:14.180
that have been there since the beginning of
colonialism.

00:20:14.180 --> 00:20:15.560
And the reason for that was they'd all fled.

00:20:15.560 --> 00:20:20.490
There were like three generations of Greeks
and various people from Eastern Europe and

00:20:20.490 --> 00:20:25.770
people who had really been there for a hundred
years, but they didn't have citizenship and

00:20:25.770 --> 00:20:30.130
people were leaving their factories and getting
the hell out of there.

00:20:30.130 --> 00:20:33.340
So she said, "We hear there's gonna be a blood
bath.

00:20:33.340 --> 00:20:35.179
How soon can you get there?"

00:20:35.179 --> 00:20:36.179
[laughter]

00:20:36.179 --> 00:20:39.710
I'm like, "Oh, let's see.

00:20:39.710 --> 00:20:45.549
I gotta get my yellow fever shot, but I think
I can make it by sundown."

00:20:45.549 --> 00:20:47.640
But in fact what the problem was no planes
were going in.

00:20:47.640 --> 00:20:49.549
They had stopped all the international traffic.

00:20:49.549 --> 00:20:55.600
So, I ended up going into Brazzaville, which
is in the other Congo across the river and

00:20:55.600 --> 00:20:59.900
got what was truly the last, at that moment
in time, the last ferry over.

00:20:59.900 --> 00:21:03.690
And this was, and I had to, these two Greek
guys who had fled a month before came on the

00:21:03.690 --> 00:21:04.690
plane with me.

00:21:04.690 --> 00:21:07.990
I say Greek, but they were, like I said, third
generation.

00:21:07.990 --> 00:21:10.429
They were going back to see their factory.

00:21:10.429 --> 00:21:15.490
So, it was so lucky for me because they spoke
English and I spoke French, but not--.

00:21:15.490 --> 00:21:19.710
They speak French there, too, in the Congo,
but not so great.

00:21:19.710 --> 00:21:21.130
And so, they were like, "OK, OK.

00:21:21.130 --> 00:21:22.130
We're gonna get this ferry."

00:21:22.130 --> 00:21:27.370
And they helped me get the ferry and they
said, "You better stuff all that equipment."

00:21:27.370 --> 00:21:30.520
So, I get on the ferry like I'm like nine
months pregnant.

00:21:30.520 --> 00:21:31.520
And they had heard.

00:21:31.520 --> 00:21:34.730
They had some kind of walkie-talkie and they'd
heard that people were stealing everything

00:21:34.730 --> 00:21:39.750
off of everybody as soon as the ferry landed
on the other end because it was quite chaotic.

00:21:39.750 --> 00:21:41.830
And, but somehow, I don't know.

00:21:41.830 --> 00:21:46.150
I they were around me and we plunged through
and we got there.

00:21:46.150 --> 00:21:48.720
And we went straight to their factory and
they took me before the hotel.

00:21:48.720 --> 00:21:54.640
And that factory--they opened the door and
the factory is empty, stripped of everything,

00:21:54.640 --> 00:21:56.029
electrical, everything.

00:21:56.029 --> 00:22:05.040
And just that deep in slippers, in flip-flops,
because people had run so fast out of there

00:22:05.040 --> 00:22:08.210
that they ran out of their shoes.

00:22:08.210 --> 00:22:13.690
It was a stunning sight and I wish I'd had
an iPhone with a camera.

00:22:13.690 --> 00:22:19.600
I mean, I go to the hotel and it's pretty
much water for an hour a day.

00:22:19.600 --> 00:22:22.790
All the reporters were put on the fifth floor--pretty
empty.

00:22:22.790 --> 00:22:23.970
I mean, but still.

00:22:23.970 --> 00:22:28.380
This fancy intercontinental hotel and there
were these guys walking around with what looked

00:22:28.380 --> 00:22:32.299
like bowling balls on their ears.

00:22:32.299 --> 00:22:35.350
They were walking around with these big black
things that they were doing this.

00:22:35.350 --> 00:22:37.600
And I'm like, "Who are they?

00:22:37.600 --> 00:22:38.600
And what is that?"

00:22:38.600 --> 00:22:43.830
And they were like early adopters of phones,
these kind of things that I think people did

00:22:43.830 --> 00:22:46.240
have in their cars in 1991.

00:22:46.240 --> 00:22:48.560
But they were carrying them around.

00:22:48.560 --> 00:22:50.290
And I said, "Well, who are they?"

00:22:50.290 --> 00:22:55.400
And they were diamond smugglers, very fancily,
beautifully dressed with these.

00:22:55.400 --> 00:22:58.240
And you're like, "Yeah, that's who has all
the equipment, right?"

00:22:58.240 --> 00:22:59.240
[laughter]

00:22:59.240 --> 00:23:00.240
The diamond smugglers.

00:23:00.240 --> 00:23:01.240
They figured it out.

00:23:01.240 --> 00:23:02.240
They needed it.

00:23:02.240 --> 00:23:03.240
They're working it.

00:23:03.240 --> 00:23:04.240
But for the rest of us, it was the same thing.

00:23:04.240 --> 00:23:07.060
You had to go to people's houses and set it
up.

00:23:07.060 --> 00:23:11.370
But one time, I tried and I had to make a
phone, I got ill and I was supposed to be

00:23:11.370 --> 00:23:13.260
there three weeks, but I had to get out.

00:23:13.260 --> 00:23:14.900
And there really wasn't a way to get out.

00:23:14.900 --> 00:23:16.450
It wasn't easy.

00:23:16.450 --> 00:23:19.250
I didn't know how to get a flight out of Brazzaville,
so I tried to call NPR.

00:23:19.250 --> 00:23:25.510
I did call NPR and say I needed a flight just
a little earlier, just a simple change.

00:23:25.510 --> 00:23:27.620
It would be simple today.

00:23:27.620 --> 00:23:33.100
But then, it took three days for the phone
call to come back to me.

00:23:33.100 --> 00:23:38.320
There was a business room and you went in
and you put in a call.

00:23:38.320 --> 00:23:40.559
"I'd like to put in a call to this number."

00:23:40.559 --> 00:23:43.160
Three days later, they knocked on my door
and said, which was OK.

00:23:43.160 --> 00:23:44.900
I didn't need to get out that fast.

00:23:44.900 --> 00:23:48.960
Three days later, they knocked on my room
and said, "Your call is waiting for you downstairs."

00:23:48.960 --> 00:23:52.440
So, I go down and I talk fast 'cause I knew
it was expensive.

00:23:52.440 --> 00:23:57.179
But I never knew how expensive it was until
I turned, I got billed at the end of the--.

00:23:57.179 --> 00:24:01.680
It was like a nine-minute call and it was
300 and change dollars.

00:24:01.680 --> 00:24:08.059
That, that, and the way I got out was it was
a little Christian flight, like a one-seater

00:24:08.059 --> 00:24:09.059
or two-seater.

00:24:09.059 --> 00:24:10.500
Only room for one more.

00:24:10.500 --> 00:24:12.059
And they didn't organize it.

00:24:12.059 --> 00:24:15.520
The hotel organized because there was no way
to get out.

00:24:15.520 --> 00:24:18.190
There was no ferry running across the river.

00:24:18.190 --> 00:24:22.900
So, I mean, the way that they do it now--you
hear all these stories as you're going along--these

00:24:22.900 --> 00:24:29.490
were things that happened without anybody
knowing what you're going through because

00:24:29.490 --> 00:24:31.620
there was no communication.

00:24:31.620 --> 00:24:33.730
I wanted to open it up for questions.

00:24:33.730 --> 00:24:36.010
I wanted to, but I do wanna do one thing.

00:24:36.010 --> 00:24:37.010
I wanna play.

00:24:37.010 --> 00:24:40.400
God, it might take six minutes, right?

00:24:40.400 --> 00:24:42.299
You all know Rwanda, right?

00:24:42.299 --> 00:24:44.950
You know what happened in 1994 in Rwanda.

00:24:44.950 --> 00:24:47.110
Half a million people killed.

00:24:47.110 --> 00:24:54.140
A terrible slaughter of the mostly ethnic
Hutus, Tutsis killed by Hutus.

00:24:54.140 --> 00:24:58.299
So, I'm gonna play a four-minute story and
open it up for questions.

00:24:58.299 --> 00:25:03.549
And the reason I wanna play it is it's a radio
story by one of our reporters, Michael Skoler,

00:25:03.549 --> 00:25:12.010
who was with us, up with me or down rather,
in Johannesburg covering the Mandela inauguration--the

00:25:12.010 --> 00:25:13.670
vote and the inauguration.

00:25:13.670 --> 00:25:18.450
And the vote took a really long time to count
so that it delayed like three weeks what we

00:25:18.450 --> 00:25:21.080
thought would be done in a day or two.

00:25:21.080 --> 00:25:23.510
It was delayed right up to the day of the
inauguration.

00:25:23.510 --> 00:25:25.740
And so Michael--.

00:25:25.740 --> 00:25:27.750
Here's the thing with foreign correspondents.

00:25:27.750 --> 00:25:31.400
They run into where everyone else is running
out of.

00:25:31.400 --> 00:25:35.360
And he was desperate to get back to Rwanda
'cause he was out of Nairobi.

00:25:35.360 --> 00:25:39.080
And I was desperate to stay and cover the
inauguration 'cause I love South Africa and

00:25:39.080 --> 00:25:40.080
was there.

00:25:40.080 --> 00:25:43.210
So, we made a deal where I stayed for the
inauguration, which was nice.

00:25:43.210 --> 00:25:45.770
Anyway, he, Michael is the second one.

00:25:45.770 --> 00:25:47.730
He's the second one.

00:25:47.730 --> 00:25:52.880
He sent this story, very much in the way I
just described--1994--you could not have heard

00:25:52.880 --> 00:25:56.750
this story 'till a week after it happened,
maybe three days.

00:25:56.750 --> 00:25:57.750
Maybe.

00:25:57.750 --> 00:25:58.750
Three and a half days.

00:25:58.750 --> 00:26:00.260
And it's a very long, it's a 21-minute long
story.

00:26:00.260 --> 00:26:02.000
I'm not gonna play 21 minutes.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:10.049
But there is one part of the idea of trying
to explain, in a book, what we did and what

00:26:10.049 --> 00:26:14.299
you heard on the radio and this was, I wanted
to use this because it was one of these really

00:26:14.299 --> 00:26:15.299
stunning stories.

00:26:15.299 --> 00:26:17.830
He got some big awards for it, too.

00:26:17.830 --> 00:26:20.750
He was there ahead of a lot of people.

00:26:20.750 --> 00:26:26.720
The difference between what you hear and what
you'll see if you see any quotes on the page

00:26:26.720 --> 00:26:32.590
because it's all in the sound in a way, profound
as his story was.

00:26:32.590 --> 00:26:34.790
And what's happened is, and I'll just do the
set up.

00:26:34.790 --> 00:26:37.059
It's probably gonna take me two minutes to
do the set up, but let me quickly just do

00:26:37.059 --> 00:26:38.059
the set up.

00:26:38.059 --> 00:26:42.140
And that was that he had gone in and all this
killing had happened, but it was really hard

00:26:42.140 --> 00:26:43.140
to cover.

00:26:43.140 --> 00:26:45.070
It was really hard for people to understand
it was happening.

00:26:45.070 --> 00:26:49.450
If you wonder sometimes why people didn't
intervene earlier, like the United States,

00:26:49.450 --> 00:26:51.500
it honestly went fast.

00:26:51.500 --> 00:26:54.510
And it was weird because it retail killing.

00:26:54.510 --> 00:26:57.880
People were not killed by bombs or rockets
or IEDs.

00:26:57.880 --> 00:27:03.770
They were killed one on one with machetes
and versions of machetes.

00:27:03.770 --> 00:27:11.060
So this six-week period, these Hutu groups
managed to rampage across the country and

00:27:11.060 --> 00:27:15.460
kill, by hand, somewhere in the neighborhood
of half a million people.

00:27:15.460 --> 00:27:20.970
So, that wasn't really getting out very well
and at the point at which people didn't know

00:27:20.970 --> 00:27:22.780
much about it, this story came on the air.

00:27:22.780 --> 00:27:23.780
[plays sound clip]

