Front, or RPF.

00:27:31.559 --> 00:27:36.620
The RPF insisted I travel with two soldiers
"for my own protection," they said, though

00:27:36.620 --> 00:27:38.630
that hardly seemed necessary.

00:27:38.630 --> 00:27:40.419
The countryside was empty.

00:27:40.419 --> 00:27:45.880
We passed miles of deserted villages, fields
of sorghum, beans and bananas with no one

00:27:45.880 --> 00:27:47.130
to harvest them.

00:27:47.130 --> 00:27:51.720
Eerie, since Rwanda is one of the most densely
populated countries in the world.

00:27:51.720 --> 00:27:56.370
Sometimes, the car would fill with the smell
of rotting flesh and we would notice corpses

00:27:56.370 --> 00:28:00.210
lying in a field or by the side of an abandoned
house.

00:28:00.210 --> 00:28:04.200
Those who had been killed here were almost
all from the Tutsi ethnic group, like the

00:28:04.200 --> 00:28:05.929
rebel soldiers with me.

00:28:05.929 --> 00:28:11.419
Other Rwandans, those of the majority Hutu
group, had fled, afraid the RPF would kill

00:28:11.419 --> 00:28:14.800
them in revenge for the slaughter of Tutsis.

00:28:14.800 --> 00:28:20.290
But occasionally, I found places crowded with
people, people too fearful to go back to their

00:28:20.290 --> 00:28:22.070
villages and homes.

00:28:22.070 --> 00:28:24.230
[crowd chatter]

00:28:24.230 --> 00:28:29.309
In a town called Gahini, 30 miles east of
the capital Kigali, the crowd around me contained

00:28:29.309 --> 00:28:34.070
old women and some younger women, small children,
but very few men.

00:28:34.070 --> 00:28:39.200
And as I asked why they were here, they started
to lift their clothes.

00:28:39.200 --> 00:28:42.760
[woman speaking]

00:28:42.760 --> 00:28:45.400
This woman is showing us her legs and arms.

00:28:45.400 --> 00:28:48.900
They have raised long wounds on them.

00:28:48.900 --> 00:28:53.250
They look like maybe they're burns.

00:28:53.250 --> 00:28:54.620
Those are burns.

00:28:54.620 --> 00:28:56.080
[women speaking]

00:28:56.080 --> 00:29:01.450
And in her nose, there's kind of a crease
now that's healed over the scar and she said

00:29:01.450 --> 00:29:05.590
that was a spear that went in through her
nose.

00:29:05.590 --> 00:29:11.840
And here's a little girl in a pretty flower
dress lifting up her skirt to show burn marks

00:29:11.840 --> 00:29:18.000
on her knees and legs, and a bandage.

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:24.020
And here's a little boy who has lifted his
shirt to show a wound from a spear, right

00:29:24.020 --> 00:29:26.840
in the middle of his back between his shoulders.

00:29:26.840 --> 00:29:28.320
[woman speaking]

00:29:28.320 --> 00:29:33.179
Mainly the boys.

00:29:33.179 --> 00:29:34.590
Even the babies.

00:29:34.590 --> 00:29:35.799
Why?

00:29:35.799 --> 00:29:38.220
Por qua?

00:29:38.220 --> 00:29:40.650
[woman speaking]

00:29:40.650 --> 00:29:43.200
In order to get rid of the Tutsi race.

00:29:43.200 --> 00:29:44.760
&gt;&gt;Woman #1: Yes.

00:29:44.760 --> 00:29:49.159
&gt;&gt;Michael Skoler: The planned killing of a
race--genocide.

00:29:49.159 --> 00:29:53.539
Foreign nations have been hesitant to label
the Rwanda massacre as genocide because that

00:29:53.539 --> 00:29:55.429
would force them to act.

00:29:55.429 --> 00:29:59.540
But the evidence that genocide has been occurring
here is hard to ignore.

00:29:59.540 --> 00:30:04.340
Those in Gahini told me to go to Kerubanda
a few miles away to see for myself what had

00:30:04.340 --> 00:30:09.049
happened to their mostly Tutsi families and
friends who, like them, had sought refuge

00:30:09.049 --> 00:30:13.960
in a church there, but who never made it out
again.

00:30:13.960 --> 00:30:18.919
As I drove up to a set of orange brick church
buildings, I had to clamp a bandana tightly

00:30:18.919 --> 00:30:20.580
over my nose and mouth.

00:30:20.580 --> 00:30:22.770
The stench was unbearable.

00:30:22.770 --> 00:30:24.000
[pause]

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:31.270
I'm outside the church and there are maybe
two or three dozen bodies.

00:30:31.270 --> 00:30:37.140
In the heat here in Rwanda, many of the bodies
are already almost fully decomposed.

00:30:37.140 --> 00:30:41.250
You can see some skulls, some backbones.

00:30:41.250 --> 00:30:47.330
There are what seem to be women in brightly
colored clothing as well as children lying

00:30:47.330 --> 00:30:48.840
about.

00:30:48.840 --> 00:30:56.919
This is amidst what is a very beautiful area
of eucalyptus trees and pine trees.

00:30:56.919 --> 00:30:59.610
[footsteps]

00:30:59.610 --> 00:31:03.190
There are bodies scattered all over the church.

00:31:03.190 --> 00:31:12.270
The blood on the floor is so thick it's dried
to kind of a muddy brown dust that may be,

00:31:12.270 --> 00:31:14.970
in some places, a quarter of an inch thick.

00:31:14.970 --> 00:31:17.790
Most of the bodies are black and then decomposing.

00:31:17.790 --> 00:31:22.289
They, some lie on mattresses, some on the
floor.

00:31:22.289 --> 00:31:24.400
Some are covered with blankets.

00:31:24.400 --> 00:31:31.390
By the altar, there are probably about 30
bodies clustered around.

00:31:31.390 --> 00:31:36.690
One is the body of an infant with the parents,
it seems, on either side.

00:31:36.690 --> 00:31:42.360
There's a suitcase that is open and torn apart
in front of the altar.

00:31:42.360 --> 00:31:51.179
On the floor of the church, you can see baskets,
plastic water cans, pails, combs, brushes,

00:31:51.179 --> 00:31:58.669
sandals, sneakers, tins of food, a bottle
of talcum powder.

00:31:58.669 --> 00:32:04.000
The windows, stained glass windows on either
side, are broken.

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:08.090
There are wooden pews that have been thrown
against them.

00:32:08.090 --> 00:32:15.440
Above the whole scene, above the altar, is
a small wooden statue of Christ with one hand

00:32:15.440 --> 00:32:16.440
raised.

00:32:16.440 --> 00:32:17.440
[end clip]

00:32:17.440 --> 00:32:19.430
&gt;&gt;Renee Montagne: Gee.

00:32:19.430 --> 00:32:23.620
I mean, I'm even like woo.

00:32:23.620 --> 00:32:29.740
What happened there, and happens I think on
NPR regularly and many times in a much happier

00:32:29.740 --> 00:32:35.490
fashion, is that there are things you can't
even imagine.

00:32:35.490 --> 00:32:38.070
In this case, too hellish to imagine.

00:32:38.070 --> 00:32:44.789
But when you hear something like this, it
becomes really impossible to not think about

00:32:44.789 --> 00:32:46.670
it or to ignore it.

00:32:46.670 --> 00:32:50.429
And that's a particular slice of what we do.

00:32:50.429 --> 00:32:58.240
That is, bringing it to you, but as long as
it took him to get this on the radio, it had

00:32:58.240 --> 00:32:59.240
to of.

00:32:59.240 --> 00:33:01.840
I mean, I wasn't there talking to Mike about
it, but Michael about it, but three, four

00:33:01.840 --> 00:33:02.840
days.

00:33:02.840 --> 00:33:03.840
I just know that's five days maybe.

00:33:03.840 --> 00:33:04.840
He had to get out of that place.

00:33:04.840 --> 00:33:10.169
He had to, there was just no, there were no
satellite phones or anything remotely like

00:33:10.169 --> 00:33:11.169
that.

00:33:11.169 --> 00:33:12.400
Computer, he probably had no computer with
him.

00:33:12.400 --> 00:33:16.610
Probably did it all by hand on a paper.

00:33:16.610 --> 00:33:19.320
It still was very, very immediate.

00:33:19.320 --> 00:33:27.730
You were still unfortunately walking with
him through this space, this little bit of

00:33:27.730 --> 00:33:29.830
hell.

00:33:29.830 --> 00:33:32.250
This is only another minute and then I'll
just turn it to questions.

00:33:32.250 --> 00:33:34.110
This is what happens today.

00:33:34.110 --> 00:33:39.559
And this is from the last time I was in Afghanistan
and it's only, like I say, it's a minute and

00:33:39.559 --> 00:33:40.559
20 seconds.

00:33:40.559 --> 00:33:43.160
But it's actually about five, six minutes
on the air.

00:33:43.160 --> 00:33:44.160
Seven or eight minutes on the air.

00:33:44.160 --> 00:33:45.160
[plays audio clip]

00:33:45.160 --> 00:33:46.160
&gt;&gt;David Green: This is "Morning Edition" from
NPR news.

00:33:46.160 --> 00:33:47.160
I'm David Green.

00:33:47.160 --> 00:33:48.160
&gt;&gt;Steve Inskeep: And I'm Steve Inskeep.

00:33:48.160 --> 00:33:49.160
Good morning.

00:33:49.160 --> 00:33:51.270
An attack on Kabul, Afghanistan is over.

00:33:51.270 --> 00:33:56.360
Attackers took control of a building that
had a clear line of fire down to the US Embassy

00:33:56.360 --> 00:33:59.610
and NATO headquarters in the heart of the
city.

00:33:59.610 --> 00:34:04.970
And it's taken 20 hours for Afghan forces
to finally clear that building.

00:34:04.970 --> 00:34:09.879
It is inside that building that we have found
NPR's Renee Montagne and Quil Lawrence.

00:34:09.879 --> 00:34:10.879
Hello to you both.

00:34:10.879 --> 00:34:11.879
&gt;&gt;Quil Lawrence: Good morning, Steve.

00:34:11.879 --> 00:34:12.879
&gt;&gt;Renee Montagne: Good morning, Steve.

00:34:12.879 --> 00:34:13.879
&gt;&gt;Steve Inskeep: What do you see there?

00:34:13.879 --> 00:34:19.270
&gt;&gt;Renee Montagne: Quil and I are both standing
on the tenth floor of this 12 story high rise,

00:34:19.270 --> 00:34:20.820
here in the middle of Kabul.

00:34:20.820 --> 00:34:25.359
And not too far from us are the bodies of
four of the attackers.

00:34:25.359 --> 00:34:29.980
There's two more bodies in the staircase as
it goes down.

00:34:29.980 --> 00:34:33.610
We're looking around and this was clearly
the site of a huge fight.

00:34:33.610 --> 00:34:38.240
We're told this was where the fight was the
fiercest, right here in this room.

00:34:38.240 --> 00:34:44.839
The walls are pock-marked with all kinds of
holes from the incoming fire from Afghan and

00:34:44.839 --> 00:34:46.919
international community forces.

00:34:46.919 --> 00:34:50.330
As you said, the target was the American Embassy.

00:34:50.330 --> 00:34:55.639
And looking out of one of these big, open
windows, there's a clear line of sight to

00:34:55.639 --> 00:34:56.639
the Embassy.

00:34:56.639 --> 00:35:01.580
It's a perfect target from this distance for
something like a rocket-propelled grenade.

00:35:01.580 --> 00:35:02.580
[end clip]

00:35:02.580 --> 00:35:05.040
&gt;&gt;Renee Montagne: I mean, it went on and on.

00:35:05.040 --> 00:35:09.040
But that was like, not live actually, although
it could've been.

00:35:09.040 --> 00:35:12.191
But an hour, 45 minutes before we went on
the air.

00:35:12.191 --> 00:35:13.940
Maybe even 15 minutes before it went on the
air.

00:35:13.940 --> 00:35:17.030
So, that, like that's 20 years right there.

00:35:17.030 --> 00:35:19.090
No, 18.

00:35:19.090 --> 00:35:21.980
As you can see, I could go on, but I won't.

00:35:21.980 --> 00:35:22.980
I won't.

00:35:22.980 --> 00:35:26.790
There must be things you wanna know at NPR
that I haven't got to.

00:35:26.790 --> 00:35:29.820
So, let me just stop for a moment and ask
for questions.

00:35:29.820 --> 00:35:33.330
&gt;&gt;Male #1: Is there really an NPR voice?

00:35:33.330 --> 00:35:36.830
Do you all take elocution lessons?

00:35:36.830 --> 00:35:38.790
[Renee Montagne laughs]

00:35:38.790 --> 00:35:44.330
And, because there's a very distinctive accent
on NPR, a [ ] pronunciation of sorts.

00:35:44.330 --> 00:35:48.450
&gt;&gt;Renee Montagne: Well, it seems to my ear
just the opposite.

00:35:48.450 --> 00:35:51.490
It sounds like some people ought to take elocution
lessons.

00:35:51.490 --> 00:35:52.490
[laughter]

00:35:52.490 --> 00:35:58.930
I mean, we do not discriminate against people
who have adenoidal voices and high voices

00:35:58.930 --> 00:36:00.570
and who talk with a sing-song.

00:36:00.570 --> 00:36:10.570
And I think the difference between us and,
as I think in commercial radio, even to this

00:36:10.570 --> 00:36:15.960
day is, I think we don't, we actually do employ
voice coaches once in a while.

00:36:15.960 --> 00:36:22.300
But really, people get hired in and whoever
they really are is how they sound on the radio.

00:36:22.300 --> 00:36:25.390
And I think while maybe in a weird way it
sounds the same is because I think what's

00:36:25.390 --> 00:36:28.691
the same about is everybody has, speaks in
their natural voices.

00:36:28.691 --> 00:36:34.690
They're voices are, I mean, I'm obviously
talking a lot faster and I know.

00:36:34.690 --> 00:36:35.890
I don't make an effort.

00:36:35.890 --> 00:36:36.980
It just happens.

00:36:36.980 --> 00:36:40.839
I put on headsets, I'm talking in front of
a mic and I can hear myself, you know?

00:36:40.839 --> 00:36:42.690
And I don't, didn't use to like that.

00:36:42.690 --> 00:36:47.369
But if I hear myself, I slow down, but I don't
like sit there thinking "slow down."

00:36:47.369 --> 00:36:49.089
I just slow down.

00:36:49.089 --> 00:36:51.060
But for the most part, my voice is my voice.

00:36:51.060 --> 00:36:52.060
Steve Inskeep voice is--.

00:36:52.060 --> 00:36:58.170
Sometimes, you get Noah Adams, who of course
was with us from the beginning practically.

00:36:58.170 --> 00:37:01.230
Bob Edwards.

00:37:01.230 --> 00:37:07.609
Robert Siegel, to some extent, with these
low, deep, maybe traditional-sounding voices.

00:37:07.609 --> 00:37:11.850
But I sort of think the office, I think what's
the same is we all sound like ourselves.

00:37:11.850 --> 00:37:14.640
So, that's so different that it's an NPR sound.

00:37:14.640 --> 00:37:15.960
Does that make sense?

00:37:15.960 --> 00:37:22.510
&gt;&gt;Male #1: Well, I know that in contrast with
BBC, it used to sound like NPR and has taken

00:37:22.510 --> 00:37:23.510
a deliberate attempt to emphasize regional
accents.

00:37:23.510 --> 00:37:24.510
&gt;&gt;Renee Montagne: I know.

00:37:24.510 --> 00:37:25.510
Yes, I know.

00:37:25.510 --> 00:37:26.510
I hear it, too.

00:37:26.510 --> 00:37:27.510
I hear it when I get up at eleven.

00:37:27.510 --> 00:37:29.400
They play a PM at night.

00:37:29.400 --> 00:37:34.830
They play "The Morning Show" on KPCC, so it's
like my "Morning Edition."

00:37:34.830 --> 00:37:35.830
Yeah.

00:37:35.830 --> 00:37:37.170
And they're going with Scottish accents.

00:37:37.170 --> 00:37:41.730
They have some even clearly like, African--I'm
not sure what countries--but some slightly

00:37:41.730 --> 00:37:43.020
African accents.

00:37:43.020 --> 00:37:44.020
And yeah.

00:37:44.020 --> 00:37:45.020
They're presenters.

00:37:45.020 --> 00:37:46.020
&gt;&gt;Male #1: Yeah.

00:37:46.020 --> 00:37:47.290
&gt;&gt;Renee Montagne: They're allowing, yeah.

00:37:47.290 --> 00:37:48.410
And they didn't used to, right?

00:37:48.410 --> 00:37:50.380
It was, what is it, received accent?

00:37:50.380 --> 00:37:51.839
Look, Madhulika is from London.

00:37:51.839 --> 00:37:53.740
She's from London.

00:37:53.740 --> 00:37:56.150
When did that switch happen?

00:37:56.150 --> 00:37:57.150
Do you even remember?

00:37:57.150 --> 00:37:58.150
You don't follow.

00:37:58.150 --> 00:37:59.300
&gt;&gt;Madhulika Sikka: Well after I was looking
for a job.

00:37:59.300 --> 00:38:00.300
[laughter]

00:38:00.300 --> 00:38:01.860
&gt;&gt;Renee Montagne: Yeah, because they wouldn't
have hired you.

00:38:01.860 --> 00:38:03.450
&gt;&gt;Madhulika Sikka: They saw my name and they
wouldn't have hired me.

00:38:03.450 --> 00:38:06.050
&gt;&gt;Renee Montagne: Madhulika Sikka would not
have been on the air 20 years ago.

00:38:06.050 --> 00:38:07.680
&gt;&gt;Madhulika Sikka: It happened way after that.

00:38:07.680 --> 00:38:11.589
And I think it also happened because the BBC
started going into more regional coverage

00:38:11.589 --> 00:38:12.910
around the country.

00:38:12.910 --> 00:38:15.930
So, Scotland and North England and those kinds
of places.

00:38:15.930 --> 00:38:20.630
So, you had a shot at making it to the national
coverage of the BBC.

00:38:20.630 --> 00:38:22.720
But certainly my people were never on the
air.

00:38:22.720 --> 00:38:23.720
[chuckles]

00:38:23.720 --> 00:38:24.720
&gt;&gt;Renee Montagne: But they are now.

00:38:24.720 --> 00:38:25.720
&gt;&gt;Madhulika Sikka: But they are now.

00:38:25.720 --> 00:38:31.859
And just one thing about NPR, I mean, I think
that Renee's right that a lot of our reporters

00:38:31.859 --> 00:38:35.240
sound exactly the way they are when you meet
them.

00:38:35.240 --> 00:38:41.470
So, Ofeibea Quist-Arcton jumps out of the
radio at you and that is exactly how she sounds

00:38:41.470 --> 00:38:43.220
when you meet her.

00:38:43.220 --> 00:38:45.349
Sylvia's the same, Louisa.

00:38:45.349 --> 00:38:49.070
We do have a fair amount of Brit-type voices
on the air.

00:38:49.070 --> 00:38:50.640
&gt;&gt;Renee Montagne: Yeah.

00:38:50.640 --> 00:38:52.590
British like Ofeibea's Ghana by birth.

00:38:52.590 --> 00:38:53.800
&gt;&gt;Madhulika Sikka: Like Louisa--.

00:38:53.800 --> 00:38:56.420
&gt;&gt;Renee Montagne: But raised or educated in
Britain.

00:38:56.420 --> 00:38:57.420
&gt;&gt;Madhulika Sikka: Yeah.

00:38:57.420 --> 00:38:59.300
So, I think that, yeah, you.

00:38:59.300 --> 00:39:07.080
I think that when you, if you met our radio
voices in person, you would know exactly who

00:39:07.080 --> 00:39:09.520
they are because their voice would be so recognizable
to you.

00:39:09.520 --> 00:39:15.109
Whereas, I think a lot of commercial television
or commercial radio, there's a voice you have

00:39:15.109 --> 00:39:17.890
portray.

00:39:17.890 --> 00:39:24.450
And they do try and get the accents right
when we're saying foreign words.

00:39:24.450 --> 00:39:26.720
We agonize over that.

00:39:26.720 --> 00:39:29.540
&gt;&gt;Renee Montagne: We try.

00:39:29.540 --> 00:39:30.890
We also fix the show.

00:39:30.890 --> 00:39:33.790
I mean, there's a first run show here in California.

00:39:33.790 --> 00:39:35.590
It's at two AM.

00:39:35.590 --> 00:39:36.820
Really hardly anyone hears it.

00:39:36.820 --> 00:39:38.320
It starts at five on the East Coast.

00:39:38.320 --> 00:39:39.850
And so, we're on that schedule.

00:39:39.850 --> 00:39:45.500
And luckily, in a way from my area, my region.

00:39:45.500 --> 00:39:49.570
If you really get something wrong, like even
if you mispronounce someone's name or you

00:39:49.570 --> 00:39:53.770
get it really wrong, you have a shot at like
doing it another time--re-doing it.

00:39:53.770 --> 00:39:55.360
But I'll tell you one thing real quickly.

00:39:55.360 --> 00:39:56.510
People also often look.

00:39:56.510 --> 00:39:59.990
People say that they don't look like, people
always say it to me honestly every time I

00:39:59.990 --> 00:40:00.990
meet someone.

00:40:00.990 --> 00:40:01.990
"Oh, I thought you'd be taller."

00:40:01.990 --> 00:40:02.990
This happened four days ago.

00:40:02.990 --> 00:40:03.990
[laughter]

00:40:03.990 --> 00:40:04.990
OK.

00:40:04.990 --> 00:40:10.090
But, or blonder, even though this is darkened
hair, so I am a little blonder than this.

00:40:10.090 --> 00:40:13.859
But many times, people do look that way.

00:40:13.859 --> 00:40:17.670
There was a slight mistake in the book where
they took something out and then collapsed

00:40:17.670 --> 00:40:19.460
something and fine, you know?

00:40:19.460 --> 00:40:20.460
It was too late to fix it.

00:40:20.460 --> 00:40:24.740
It was actually me saying this where it was
attributed to a listener once said about Sylvia

00:40:24.740 --> 00:40:25.740
Poggioli.

00:40:25.740 --> 00:40:29.200
And they what the listener really said and
left me saying it.

00:40:29.200 --> 00:40:30.200
Whatever.

00:40:30.200 --> 00:40:33.040
But Sylvia Poggioli always sounded to me before,
I met her.

00:40:33.040 --> 00:40:35.170
Because I met her after I had heard her.

00:40:35.170 --> 00:40:42.010
Like, that she would have like a 1940's jacket
on and a Fedora with, and long, dark hair

00:40:42.010 --> 00:40:47.250
swept back with a press stuck in the ribbon.

00:40:47.250 --> 00:40:49.130
And she doesn't wear that hat or the press.

00:40:49.130 --> 00:40:50.130
